#statement[
  A group $G$ is cyclic if there exists an element $g in G$ such that $G = angle.l g angle.r$.
]

#intuition[
  A cyclic group is "unidimensional" in the sense that every single element can be reached just by repeating one specific generator.
]

#proof[
  This is a definition; no proof is required. However, for the atlas rigid block requirement, we note that the existence of such a generator defines the group structure.
]

#statement[
  Every bounded sequence in $RR^n$ has a convergent subsequence.
]

#intuition[
  If you have an infinite number of points trapped in a finite box, they have to "pile up" somewhere.
]

#proof[
  By the method of bisection. Since the sequence is bounded, it lies in a compact interval $[a, b]$. Subdivide the interval...
]
